1. Introduction

 This documentation is about the Remuco client, an application running on a
mobile device with J2ME and Bluetooth (JSR 82) or WiFi support. The client
communicates with the Remuco server to remotely control media players.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

2. Building

 You can skip this step if you've downloaded the binary package.

 The client uses the Ant build system (http://ant.apache.org) and Sun's
Wireless Toolkit (http://java.sun.com/products/sjwtoolkit), both must be
installed on your system. To build the client, edit the file build.properties
and adjust it to your situation. Then run:

 $ ant dist.jar

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

3. Installation

 Install the file remuco.jar and (optionally) the file remuco.jad on your
mobile device (if you build on your own in the step above: the files are in the
directory dist). How to install is device dependent - please consult the
documentation of your mobile device.

 Once the client is installed on your phone, consider to set permissions so
that Remuco is allowed to use Bluetooth or WiFi. This releases you from always
acknowledging a connection to the server (of course you need to trust Remuco :)
)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

4. Usage

 Play around with the keys and the entries in the menus, I think that's the
best way to get familiar with the client. However, you can find more detailed
information about client usage on the Remuco website http://
remuco.sourceforge.net.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

